metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #12
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: a formless beauty #43
metadata.description:
"a formless beauty" continues my exploration of pure abstract generative art. 

In this piece, I begin with a white field. An abstract pattern of rectangles are drawn on this field, using one of 12 different color palettes. On top of this, a white diamond or filled circle is drawn, and then marks (the term that IRL abstract painters will be familiar with) are drawn over the top of this. These three layers comprise the basis of the piece. 

Things are fairly deterministic so far, but this juncture, a large amount of randomness is introduced to the piece, as the image is passed through a fragment shader that applies fractal noise to the process, resulting in an image that appears to have been painted and then washed out. I would like to thank Melissa Wiederrecht for the inspiration in this regard; her Zbageti piece pushed me to explore shaders and their effect on the overall look of the piece. 

Note 1: Due to the nature of WebGL, this piece may not (probably will not) run in live mode on a mobile device. I've tested it on mobile Safari and mobile Chrome, and it will run sometimes, but the device is very unhappy with it. 

Note 2: Due to the nature of fractal noise and the preview engine in FxHash, the preview image will  be slightly different than the live view. It will give you a general idea of the piece, but the live view will be more vibrant and detailed.

Note 3: In Live view, press "s" to save a 4000x4000 PNG of the image to your system.

metadata.name: Composition #4 #46
metadata.description:
When I'm working on a problem, I never think about beauty. But when I've finished, if the solution is not beautiful... I know it's wrong.
[Buckminster Fuller]

I tried to hybridize, in a schematic way only, the architectural language of neoplasticism with some characteristics of Islamic architecture. The result seems to me to convey a certain elegance...
As with the other "Composition #" series, you can explore the model interactively in 3D space.

metadata.name: Возвышение #116
metadata.description:
Возвышение (Eng.: Elevation) is the next step of my study of Suprematism, textures and colours, partially inspired by Lazar Khidekel works. 
The work depicts the superiority of the simplest geometric forms and colours over everything else.

metadata.name: Holy Mountain #45
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

project website:
https://playman.me/projectmountain

metadata.name: Roasting Humans #12
metadata.description:
========
Concept
========
Humanists live in a world built on human bones.
The fuel of humanism is human sacrifices.

Eating flesh is natural for animals.
But humans are eating  life energy, results of work, time  of other humans.

Social status is in general about how many humans you personally can devour.
Personal freedom in general about how not to be eaten by other humans.

Sweet promises, beautiful concepts, inspiring ideas - basically ways to put  the victim on the skewer.

Humanism today is an attempt to inject anesthesia into the basic process of eating others.
Slavery must be gentle and invisible.
Weapons must be lethal and not cause suffering.
People should be polite and tolerant.
You must not feel that your blood is being sucked out.

If the victim does not feel the pain and does not scream: is the victim a plant? Is predator a vegan?

Is it better to you feel pain or inject anesthesia?
Anesthesia today is not only drugs, but entertainment.

Are you enjoy of eating others?
So check if you are on a skewer and how roasted you are.

==============
Technical Details
==============
Mangal size calculating depending on humans amount (min=5; max=111) and skewer parameters.

You can roast the bodies from different sides using the control buttons.
The bodies are divided into sectors that absorb thermal energy differently depending on the angle of rotation.
The amount of absorbed energy determines the degree of roasting.
The camera is focused on the active skewer, to select another one, press the button or select from the list.

Press the left mouse button to rotate the point of view.
Hold down the right mouse button to move the point of view.
